# UI Authoring Runtime Boundary

- Keep runtime code that builds persistent panel/row hierarchies under `Presentation/UI` to a minimum; persistent structure should be produced by `UIScene` or editor tools.
- Classes such as `UIManager` should stay in an orchestration role; as they grow, split flow across `View + Presenter + Controller` boundaries.
- If UI `*Controller : MonoBehaviour` classes grow, move Unity-boundary code into `*View` and service/use case orchestration into a plain C# `*Controller` or `*Presenter`.
- Runtime code should only perform `data bind`, `state refresh`, `visibility/tween`, and input emission; do not add gameplay decisions or price/economy rules there.
- If UI runtime reads config, use it for display text, icons, colors, ordering, or layout; purchase/reward/price decisions belong to a use case or application service.
- When a new UI feature adds runtime behavior or presenter logic, add presenter-level tests first, then change scene wiring.
- UI text/color/icon keys should be stable IDs or config; do not bind behavior to hierarchy indexes or sibling order.

## Example

```csharp
// BAD: Runtime builds the whole panel and adds a business rule
if (playerLevel > 3) { CreateUpgradePanel(); _gameState.Money -= 100; }

// GOOD: Runtime only applies view data
var layout = _upgradePresenter.BuildLayout(_gameState, _pricingConfig);
_upgradeView.Apply(layout);
```
